To ensure that the correction and discard rule (Stage B of FairLabeler) does not introduce selection bias, we performed a subgroup-level analysis, and the results are reported in Table 2. The results indicate that both operations (correction/discard rule) are applied in a balanced manner across subgroups. For instance, in the Default-sex and Bank-age tasks, the difference in massaging rates between subgroups is only 1.79% (22.12% vs. 20.33%) and 1.11% (21.88% vs. 20.77%), respectively. Similarly, discard rates remain low and comparable across privileged and unprivileged groups, such as in the Compas-sex (1.10% vs. 0.88%) and Meps16-race (3.30% vs. 2.37%) tasks. Even in cases with relatively higher intervention, such as Student-sex and German-sex tasks, the differences remain controlled, with massaging differences of 7.43% and 6.88%, and discard differences of 2.15% and 2.70%, respectively. Importantly, discard rates remain below 10% across all tasks (e.g., Adult-race: 10.24% vs. 7.05%; Heart-age: 8.18% vs. 5.60%), ensuring that no subgroup is disproportionately removed. Overall, these results demonstrate that the proposed approach applies correction and discard operations proportionally across subgroups, thereby avoiding the introduction of selection bias while improving label fairness.
